text = "[font_size=20][center][b]Initial state[/b][/center][/font_size]

Compound state uses \"initial state\" property. It is the default substate to be active:

[ul]
At statechart initialization, if a compound state is active, then its initial state is active.
On transition, if a compound state is entered, with no descendant assigned to enter, then its initial state is entered.
[/ul]

If no non-history substate is assigned as inital state, then first non-history substate will be selected.

For this test, press the test button then you'll see how compound state use its initial state.

[ul]
The compound root state select \"Init\" as initial state, since it is the first non-history substate. So before you press the test, \"Init\" is active.
On test pressed, transition invokes. \"Test\" will be entered. \"Test/B\" is assigned as initial state, so it will be entered too.
You may notice the warning on \"Test/B\" node, because its initial state assignment is invalid. During the runtime, initial state neglects invalid assignment, and fallback to first non-history substate (which is \"Test/B/X\" in this case).
[/ul]

By the way, initial state property is only used under compound mode.
"
threaded = true

